<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900813-0083</DOCNO><DOCID>900813-0083.</DOCID><HL>   UAW Official Says   `True Job Security'   Is Key to Contract</HL><DATE>08/13/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><CO>   LABOR C GM</CO><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><LP>   TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. -- A top United Auto Workers unionofficial said the union would moderate its pay demands andback three-shift production schemes at Big Three assemblyplants in exchange for &quot;true job security.&quot;   &quot;I think management is right that they need moreflexibility to keep their plants running at capacity and tokeep jobs in this country,&quot; Stan Marshall, the UAW vicepresident leading the union's negotiations with ChryslerCorp., said Friday at an industry conference here.</LP><TEXT>   But Mr. Marshall said the union has no interest inChrysler's proposal to pay UAW members with stock in exchangefor wage and work-practice concessions. He also said theunion isn't interested in Chrysler's proposal to payemployees at certain factories for achieving specificproductivity goals, such as reducing absenteeism or improvingquality.   Chrysler officials had no comment on Mr. Marshall'sremarks. Both General Motors Corp. and Chrysler have madeunion approval of three-shift production a major objective oftheir current national contract negotiations with the UAW.   Analysts say expanding vehicle production over threeshifts from two could yield as much as $200 million more ayear in gross profits from a plant building a popular model.GM credits three-shift work schedules for helping to producerecord profits in the past three years at its Europeanoperations.</TEXT></DOC>